{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958062001/0328.xml":{"full_text":"v Summit County Labor Newt\nMtiiW Emmry Friday ly\nI THE SUMMIT COUNTY LABOR NEWS\nA Nmm-PmrlUmm Nmmpmpnr pmkHshmA im Am bmot faunUi\nV OrgmmlmmA Libor mmi the entiro Commwmthy.\nv 1 Editorial, Advertising and Printing: Offices\n920 SOUTH HIGH STREET Telephotw\u2014PO 2-1110\nAKRON 11, OHIO _\nTbt EXCHANGE PRINTING Co. .....Publisher\nMartin Bliman ....Editor\nAlex Eigemnacht.Contributing Editor\nT\"^\u00abi^iri*eoorataiii\u00abiSiiriftiy4r^ir5nSrt^Sejriir\nAkron, Ohio, under act of Karah t, 1897.\nt. Yaarly Sqfaacription in Advance....$8.00\nKm af Interest from the verloue local unions' under the Jurisdiction of\nthe Congress of Industrial Organizations, Akron Industrial Union\nthe American Federation of Labor and the Akron Federation of Is\nsolicited. All news matter should reach the editorial office of the Summit\nCounty Labor News not later than Tuesday noon.\nThe Summit County Labor News accepts advertisements from firms not\non the unfair list of the Central Bodies. It must be understood, however,\nthat the editorial policy of this publication is affected in no way by such\nadvertisements.\nQuote for the Week\n\u201cI have said before that the adoption of a!) excellent, hard\nhitting set of ethical practices code is one of the most significant\nand admirable steps in the history of the American Trade Union\nMovement. And I know of no other group in the country\u2014politi\ncians, businessmen, lawyers, or anyone else\u2014which has gone as\nfar as the Labor Movement has in setting up proper fiduciary\nstandards to govern their own officials.\u201d (U. S. Senator John F.\nKennedy)\nGood Relations Are Good Business\nThere was considerable gratification in the announcement by\nRemington Rand that they are again sponsoring the \u201cMiss Union\nSecretary\u201d Contest to honor the outstanding female office em\nployee of a labor union in the United Statess.\nFor a variety of reasons we hope that the \u201cMiss Union Secre\ntary of 1958\u201d Contest will be even more successful than last year\u2019s.\nFor one thing, we\u2019re delighted to see the \u201cUnion Secretary\u201d\nget some well-deserved recognition. The organized labor move\nment couldn\u2019t function without these devoted girls and women who\nkeep the offices running at peak efficiency.\nSecondly, the labor-management relations prevailing between\nRemington Rand and the various unions whose members it em\nploys are generally good today. Remington Rand has discovered\nthat good relations with organized labor are good business and\nthat intelligent promotion of union made products means more\nsales.\nv Remington Rand was the first manufacturer of typewriters\nand office machines to put the Union Label of the International\nAssociation of Machinists on its machines. Some Remington\nproducts now carry the label of the International Brotherhood of\nElectrical Workers.\nWe wish Remington Rand success with the \u201cMiss Union Secre\ntary of 1958\u201d Contest. Not only will it give union office workers\na chance to compete for the 23 substantial prizes\u2014first prize alone\nis a check for one thousand dollars plus a portable typewriter\nplus a week\u2019s all-expenses-paid vacation\u2014but it will also mean\nmore work and greater prosperity for our fellow unionists.\n-o\nGovernor Now Praises SUB\nIt has taken a long time but we are happy to note that Gov.\nC. William O\u2019Neill is now saying the same thing about supple\nmental unemployment benefits (SUB) that Organized Labor has\nbeen saying for some time\u2014that SUB is good for the unemployed\nand the economy as a whole.\nThe Governor had told a press conference this week that\nSUB payments would give \u201ca big economic lift to communities\nsuffering most from unemployment\u201d and give \u201chelp to people\nwho are in the greatest need.\u201d\n\u201cThese (SUB) payments, of course, are not from public\nfunds,\u201d the Governor stated. \u201cThey would not cost the taxpayers\na penny. There are not state or public funds involved.\u201d\nNot only has the Governor now spoken out publicly about the\nmerits of SUB, he has helped cut red tape and get the SUB ques\ntion before the State Supreme Court for quick consideration.\nThis is quite a switch on SUB by the Governor. Until the\nGovernor\u2019s public statement, the Administration had maintained\na position of fighting SUB and blocking SUB payments.\nIn fact, we now have the unusual picture of the Governor\npublicly praising SUB while his legal representatives argue\nagainst it before the Supreme Court. But- at least, the Governor\nhas at long last recognized the soundness of SUB.\nSUB contracts were negotiated in good faith by Labor and\nManagement. Both agreed that state compensation alone was not\nenough to sustain the jobless, that additional help was needed.\nThe unemployed need these SUB paymnts now. They have\nneeded them for many months. The Governor\u2019s change of attitude\nis welcome. But it- is unfortunate that it came so late.\nss\nOf the People, By the People, But Not FOR the People\nGood men in the U. S. Senate tried last week, but failed, to\nput more food on the tables of the unemployed and ease.the\nhumiliation of joblessness and public relief. And Ohio\u2019s two\nSenators, John W. Bricker and Frank J. Lausche, helped them fail.\nStanding with Southern Democrats and GOP right-wingers,\nBricker and Lausche voted against a series of proposals that were\noffered to help the unemployed, the aged, blind and disabled.\nThe Lausche-Bricker anti- people combine started to operate\nwhen Senator John Kennedy proposed to increase unemployment\ncompensation, extend coverage to employers of one or more work\ners and set a uniform payment period of 39 weeks. Lausche and\nBricker voted \u201cnay.\u201d The proposal was defeated.\nThen Kennedy proposed to extend benefits 16 weeks and\n-waive repayment of federal money advanced to the states for the\nadditional weeks if the states liberalized their own programs\nLausche and Bricker voted no. The amendment lost,\nv In a third effort, Senator Kennedy tried to make it compul\neory for the states to increase the duration period by 16 weeks.\nAnother \u201cnay\u201d from Ohio\u2019s Senators helped kill this attempt to\nliberalize the states\u2019 systems.\nAnd then to climax the day's performance, Bricker and\nLausche voted against a proposal to increase public\npayments to the aged, blind and disabled by about $5 a month!\nThe vote on the last proposal was 40-40. The tie vote lHHod\nthe proposal. If Ohio\u2019s Senators\u2014or just one of them\u2014-had voted\n!\u201cy*e,\u201d vie proposal would have.passed.\nInner he was one of a lonely'group of five Democrats who\nfoted against this proposal. The other four were: Byrd and\nBabeHeon of Virginia, Thurmond of South Carolina and Stennis\n\\^Stor1hSiping defeat these attempt* write\nan effective un\nim*\nUNEMPLOYMENT WILL BE\nTOR POLITICAL ISSUE\n(Clnatl\u2014a from Page OH)\nHie panels conducting' die discus\nsions consist of leaden from tbs four\nstate or five-state anas involved in\neach conference. Kwjr are assisted by\nCOPE staff members.\nDuring each\u2019session of the panel\non issues and communications, dele\ngates were asked to. list the issues\nthey hear the most talk about among\ntheir friends and neighbors. Without\nexception the first subject mentioned\nwas unemployment or the recession.\nSharp comments were heard re\ngardlng the failure of the national Ad\nministration to demonstrate any con\ncern over joblessness.\nlin the two southern conferences the\nsecond item mentioned was anti-labor\nlegislation and how to Secure repeal\nof state compulsory open-shop laws\nwhere they exist His Boehm and\nPhiladelphia conferees were more\nconcerned with the high cost of living\nand placed pending labor legislation\nthird in importance.\nOther issues raised and discussed\nwere taxes, foreign aid and tariffs,\nschools, social security and medical\ncare.\nAt one conference a sounding was\nmade on the grass-roots reaction to\nthe kind of reception given Vice Pres.\nRichard M. Nixon in South America.\n\u201cI notice,\u201d aaMI one of the dele\ngates, \"that George Meany and Bill I\nWARNS RECESSION TO\nCOST $50 BILLION\nThe current recension will coot the\nnation between $50 billion and $80\nbillion depending' on how long it takes\nto get the economy back into high\ngear.\nRunning along at Its current slug\ngish pace with little or no stimulus\nfrom business or government to speed\nrecovery, the economy is more than'\nlikely to chalk up the $80 billion loss\nfigure.\nThese estimates Oh the cost of the\nrecession have been worked out by\nthe staff of the Joint Congressional\nCommittee on the Economic Report,\nwhich produces an annual survey on\nthe Economic Report submitted to\nCongress by the Resident.\nThe committee\u2019s lose estimates\ncame as the anti-recession pragma\nin Congress Mmped along with mini\nmum support from either congres\nsional leaders or the Administration.\nIt was followed by a new govern\nment report showing that business\nspending for new plant and equipment\nfor 1958 have been revised downward\nfor the second time with the drop\nfrom last year set at 17 per cent in\ncontrast to earlier estimates of a 13\nper cent reduction.\nThe survey by the Commerce Dept,\nand the Securities Exchange Com\nmission showed estimated spending of\n$30.7 billion compared to the earlier\nestimate of $32 billion and the 1957\nfigure of $37 billion.\nA New York Timm report noted\nin addition that \"the decline in fu\nture spending could be worse than\nthe report indicates.\"\nEconomists view the decline in busi\nness spending for new plant and\nequipment as a major factor in the\nrecession and the key to speedy re\ncovery.\nOn the employment front, the gov\nernment report of a drop In unem\nployment to 4,004,000 In mid-May\ncompered to 5,120,000 In mid-April\nindicated a slight.improvement\nBut with new additions to the\nlabor force in June as graduates start\ned Job-hunting', unemployment Is ex\npected to move up sharply with some\neconomists placing the figure this\nmonth at dose to six million.\nWhile employment was showing a\ngeneral gain, Jobs In nuoiufacturing\ndeclined. 67,000 to a total of 15 million\nin May. As compared with a year\n\u2022go, manufacturing employment is\ndown 1.7 million.\nAmong Hie 4.9 million unemployed\nte May, the number out of work 15\nweeks or longer was estimated at U\nmillion. There were 600,060 who had\nbeen out of work for more than 26\nAverage weekly hours of factory\nwrokera were 38.8 or 1.2 hours below\na year ago.\nThe seasonally adjusted rate of un\nemployment in mid-May was 7.2 per\ncent, a drop from the 7,5 per cent\nIn April, but above the March rate of\n7 per cent\nla measuring the costtbg the reces\nsion. tlie congressional committee\n\u2022taff pegged the problem on the speed\nof reoovery.\nTo get hack to the Ugh employ\nemployment compensation bill, I\non a watered-down bill that willj\nor not they want federal help i\nby 18 weeks.\nHowever, the record will atai\ncent for the unemployed by Ohi\nthat they have little concern.\nWiWhlii rat'im then laat year\nand wen treated very cordially. Hat\nshould give thoae folks la the 8tate\nEvidence of lnyminy activity\namong trade uitat wives and women\nmembers came from the panel session\non women\u2019s' activities and special\nwomen\u2019s meetings held in conjunc\ntion with the conference*.'\nDelegates in Philadelphia heard the\nStory of the local women\u2019s activities\ndirector who built a program starting\nodd from a telephone book.\nOthen heard of the devoton of a\nwife who had agreed to hold a coffee\nparly for a candidate. Ike day before\nthe party was scheduled she fell down\nthe stairs of her home and fractured\nher shoulder. She had the shoulder set\nthat afternoon, held the party the fol\nlowing day, and only men went to the\nhospital for fTiiatimml\nPanels on political organization and\nregistration mid OOPE financing re\nviewed procedures and tackled the\nproblem* most often arising.\n\"Realistically,\u201d commented Mc\nDevitt, \"I know we\u2019ve got a lot of\nhard work ahead of us this year but\nyou can\u2019t come away from one of\nthese conferences without the feeling\nthat it\u2019s going to get done, regardless\nof the obstacles..\nf \"These are people who know the\nscore and they're going to do the job.\u201d\nmeat level of the pre-dump period,\nwhen unemployment was one out of\nevery 20 workers instead of the cur\nrent one out of 14, the economy\nWould have to expand at a rate of 11\nper cent\u2014a rate reached previously\nUnder the stimulus of the Korean\nWm'- '1 f\nBut even at this? rate, the commit\ntee staff estimates, Hie bin for two\nyears of slowdown and recession\nwould be more tlutui $00 billion.\nIf recovery Is ut Hie slower rate\nof 7 per cent\u2014the rate at which the\nnation recovered from the 195S-54\nstamp\u2014then the cost will run over\n$70 billion by the end of 1060.\nCurrently the economy lsv running\n'about $35 billion ay ear below a high\nemployment level if figured at a con\nservative growth rate of 3.1 per cent\na year\u2014the average of the last 00\nyoa/ra.\nIf figured at a 4.7 per cent rate\u2014a\nmore realistic rate according to many\nleading economists\u2014the loss in cur\nrent output would be figured at $60\nbillion a year. 1\nEven if the natloii recovers from\nthe current recession with unexpected\nspeed\u2014a point doubted by many\neconomists\u2014the $60 to $80 billion\nlose would be largi) enough to pay for\na wide variety of essential goods and\nservices.\nThe loss aooordingvto the Washing'\nton Post, would cover the entire cost\nof the 13-year highway program with\nabout $16 billion left over; all the\ngoods and services the federal gov\nernment will buy this year; every\nthing sold last year by auto dealers,\nfurniture, appliance, hardware and all\nother hard goods stores; and three\nyeans of state and local government\noutlays for school payrolls and build*\ntags.\nJune 30 Deadline\nFor \"Freezing\"\nS-S Disability-\nJune 30 is an important deadline\ntor totally disabled persons who have\nworked under social security. That Is\nthe 'last date on which they can1 make\napplication for the disability \u201cfreeze\u201d\ndr benefits and establish a date prior\nto July 1, 19S7 for the beginning: of\nthe disability.\nIf a disabled person applies by\nJune SO, his disability period oaa go\nback to the actual date he had to quit\nworking. This can mean higher bene\nfits for him daring his disability and\nfor him and his dependents In hte old\nRichard h. Hendrick, district social\nsecurity manager, wans that failure\nto apply by June 30 could mean great\nly reduced payments and might even\nmean kiss of all benefit rights by the\nindtvdaal and his family.\nHendrick urges ell* totally disabled\npersona who have had ooveref em\nployment to get to touch with the\nnearest social security office. \u201cUhder\nthis program,\" he say*. \u2018total disabil\nity means unable to engage to any\nsubstantial work.\u201d\nausche and Briclceg voted \u201cyee\u201d\n*ave it up to the. states whether\ni extending the\u2018payment period\nid above all future claims of coh\no\u2019s Senators and stand a\n:>v'\ni. :;A\nJ:. r\nReports Less Drop\nIn Ohio Sales Tax\nTake for Week\n'Several signs point to a firmer tone\nIn sales tax collections, Treasurer of\nState Roger W. Tracy said tUs week.\nWeekly collections woe only\nslightly bekrtr the same week a year\nago, and there was noticeable im\nprovement in several urban ooonti.es\n<jt the state, with Cuyahoga, Frank\nlin and Hamilton aB reporting col\nlections in excess of the corresponding\nweek last year.\nFar the keek ending May SI collec\ntions were $$\u00a349,822. This was $170,\n0*5. or 4.14 per cent, wider the same\nweek last year.\nWith only four weeks remaining in\nthe fiscal year, cumulative collections'\nare $203,004,201. This is a lag of\n$9,300,086 or .only 4.38 per cent, under\ncollections of $212,304,287 for the cor\nresponding period of last year.\nA breakdown of the weekly report\nshows five rural counties in the select\ngroup with collections for the year in\nexcess of last year, These are Fair\nfield, Gallia, .Meigs, Monfoe and\nWashington. The three urban coun\nties showed an aggregate gain of\n$251,846 over the same week of last\nyear.\nThe report further disclosed that\nthe eight urban counties account for\n$6,566,653 of the current cumulative\nlag Of $9,300,066. I\nMe Peak Is in State\nLegislation Post\nOarl McPeak, who since the merger\nof the AFL and CXO has been serving\nas assistant director of the AFL-CIO\nDept, of Organization, has been ap\npointed to the newly created poet of\nspecial representative for state legis\nlation.\nIn his new assignment, McPeak\nwill assist and advise AFJ>CIO state\ncentral bodies on all problems dealing\nwith state legislative matters.\nPrior to merger, McPeak was as\nsistant to the executive vice president\nof the dO and director of industrial\nunion councils, working with dO\ncouncils throughout the country. He\nwas formerly the CIO\u2019s Texas state\ndirector.\nAt Midwest Industrial Fair\nv ;v 'V\u00ab*v\nThe Mobile X-\u00abay Unit of the Sum\nnit County TUbcraikato end BnHh\nAssociation wilt continue iti summer\nx-raying- schedule during the next\ntwo weeks.\nA highlight of the schedule will be\na stay at the Midwest Industrial Shir\nto be held at TWlmadge High School\nAram now through Sunday, Juris 22.\nTubercidosia lung cancers, lung\ntumors, and heart disorders are some\nof the chest conditions disoovesed by\na chest x-ray. AS adults are urged to\nhave an x-ray once each year.,\nThis free health service is stymied\nby the sale of Chrttmias Seal and\nthe United Foundation.\nHere Is the schedule^ tints the end\nofjtrne:\nFriday, June 20\u2014Midwest Indus\ntrial Fair, TsJhnadge High School,\n78 North Avenue, 4 P. M. to 10 P. M.;\nSaturday\u2014Midwest Industrial Mr,\n1 P. M. to 10 P. H; Sunday\u2014Midwest\nIndustrial Fhlr. l P. M. to 8 P. M.;\nMonday, June 28 Tuberculosis\nCSlnic, 828 Locust Street, 10 A K\nto S:S0 P. M.; Tuesday\u2014Midwest Bob\nber Reclaiming Co* 748 Norton\nAvenue, Barberton, 10 A. M. to 4\nP. M.; Wednesday\u2014Summit County\nJail, 10 A. M. to 11 A. M. (Not open\nThe fight against cancer is far\nfrom hopeless. The death rate for\nwomen 35 to 44 has declined 25 par\ncent since 1842, according, to the\nAmerican Cancer Society. Doctors\nemphasise the importance of an early\ncheckup.\nADVIRTrSIMO AND PUBLICATION\nDPECC printing\nNEJJ Akron, Ohio\n(Pol. Adr.)\nGeorge D. Cline\nfor\nState Senator\n(4 Year Tens)\n7-8-58\nSTANLEY\nWARNER\nSTRAND\nThe boldly daring story of the first man, the first\nwoman and the first romance\n?->v Filmed In vivid living color\n\u201cADAM AND EVE\u201d\n..V\nBRIAN KEITH and DICK KORAN la r\n4i%/iA H_ in\nViolent Road\u2019\nTr*m PmrUmg Ewry Night mftmr 6 PM. 77 Somtk Hommril Strml\nWS-C-ld pao* jajtMipuaw 4ICS f; 7\nIVOIldO d0\u201c03 :v\n\u2019\u2022JO|B pub (mo\n-poq* p;OAy *\u00abaXa 40 pA\u00bb(\nMO|\u00abq Xdmo uipuj\n81 o| 91 PPM *q P|noq*\nJSUDUl BUjpOag |OU\u00abJOUI\np\u00bbtu|jcl 40 apj* auo ot\npuo j\u00abpo\u00abi 49 lpoq u; \u00abaaj\nC inoao paso|d *udm ool\n01 os aq p|Aoqt tqflij Buj\n\u2022poag 'UjoiitaXa maAiid\n<*|pq <i]qbq Butpoaj poo\u00abx\n-.,V\nto paHli). aad Berrodla Farma, Ml\nCtayakoga Street 1 PkM. to l\u00ab -I\nP. MU (Net epee to poMto);\ndear Stow Pnom\u2014Ha\nAmoco Oh StaUoa, Bootee (nail\nintenectloa, 11 A. M. to P. M.; Frt.\ntoy\u2014Community Program, Wooster\nend Rhodes Amato, 1 P. JL tofl\nP. M\u00bb; (s\nMoidajr, Jn* M totontonto\nCltolc, 8M Lecaat Street, It A. ML-V\ntoIMP.E\nBsamss Register\nPeacock NwiMcy\nTry Ue For Better Plants\nVs **'y*'*-\u2022 OURS CROW 4V\n:>r\n721 S.\nMO 6-4922\n-v*\n\n6-27\nAKRON, OHIO\n\nCmpfi